4 October 1743","1790":"1790","1690":"1690"," 6 AUG 1755":"6 August 1755","Eschwege, Hessen Kassel, Germany":"Eschwege, Hesse-Nassau, Prussia, Germany","Eschwege,Hessen Kassel Germany":"Eschwege, Hesse-Nassau, Prussia, Germany","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Hopffner","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["German: variant of <b>Höffner</b> (see   Hoffner  ). Compare   Hoefner  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Hoffner","meanings":["German (also <b>Höffner</b>): status name for a prosperous small farmer, from an agent noun derivative of Middle Low German <i>huove</i>, a measure of land. See also   Huber  , compare   Hoeffner   and   Hofner   2.","German (also <b>Höffner</b>): variant of   Hofner   1.","Jewish (Ashkenazic): variant of   Hopfer  ."]}]},{"name":"Marcus","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["The original Latin form of   Mark  , of unknown derivation; it may possibly be connected with <i>Mars</i>, the name of the Roman god of war, or the adjective <i>mas</i> ‘male, virile’ (genitive <i>maris</i>). This was one of the very small number of Roman given names of the classical period. There were only about a dozen of these in general use, with perhaps another dozen confined to particular families. <i>Marcus</i> has been in use in the English-speaking world since the 16th century if not earlier; in the 20th century it enjoyed a considerable increase in popularity. As an African-American name it is sometimes bestowed in honour of the Black Consciousness leader  Marcus Garvey  (  1887–1940 )."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Henrich","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["from <i>heim</i> ‘home’ + <i>rīc</i> ‘power’.  See  Henry ."],"variants":[{"name":"Henry","meanings":["A perennially popular given name, of Continental Germanic origin, from <i>haim</i> ‘home’ + <i>rīc</i> ‘power, ruler’. It was an Old French name, adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. It has been borne by eight kings of England. Not until the 17th century did the form <i>Henry</i> (as opposed to   Harry  ) become the standard vernacular form, mainly under the influence of the Latin form <i>Henricus</i> and French <i>Henri</i>."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Marcus Henrich Hopffner was born on 16 June 1711, in Eschwege, Hesse-Nassau, Prussia, Germany as the son of Johann Bernhardt Hopffner. He married Anna Maria Sybille Lenning on 4 October 1743, in Eschwege, Hesse-Nassau, Prussia, Germany. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died after 1755."},"et":{"16 JUN 1711–AFT. 1755":"16. juuni 1711–pärast 1755","1711–1755":"1711–1755","1710–1790":"1710–1790","1755–1831":"1755–1831","1690–1750":"1690–1750","16 JUN 1711":"16. juuni 1711","AFT. 1755":"pärast 1755","1755":"1755","1711":"1711","1831":"1831","1710":"1710","3 MAR 1750":"3. märts 1750","1750":"1750","4 OCT 1743":"4. oktoober 1743","1790":"1790","1690":"1690"," 6 AUG 1755":"6. august 1755","Eschwege, Hessen Kassel, Germany":"Kreis Eschwege, Hessen-Nassau, Preußen, Saksamaa","Eschwege,Hessen Kassel Germany":"Kreis Eschwege, Hessen-Nassau, Preußen, Saksamaa"},"fi":{"16 JUN 1711–AFT. 1755":"16. kesäkuuta 1711–1755 jälkeen","1711–1755":"1711–1755","1710–1790":"1710–1790","1755–1831":"1755–1831","1690–1750":"1690–1750","16 JUN 1711":"16. kesäkuuta 1711","AFT. 1755":"1755 jälkeen","1755":"1755","1711":"1711","1831":"1831","1710":"1710","3 MAR 1750":"3. maaliskuuta 1750","1750":"1750","4 OCT 1743":"4. lokakuuta 1743","1790":"1790","1690":"1690"," 6 AUG 1755":"6. elokuuta 1755","Eschwege, Hessen Kassel, Germany":"Kreis Eschwege, Hessen-Nassau, Preußen, Saksa","Eschwege,Hessen Kassel Germany":"Kreis Eschwege, Hessen-Nassau, Preußen, Saksa"},"fr":{"16 JUN 1711–AFT. 1755":"16 juin 1711–après 1755","1711–1755":"1711–1755","1710–1790":"1710–1790","1755–1831":"1755–1831","1690–1750":"1690–1750"